<br>
Yes Traxx, I can do math as well.  The ratio on the dagger is better but the sword is faster.  You are advising another warrior to give up a weapon with a superior ratio for speed.  Why not me too?  At my level my piercing skill is less than my 1HS so my attack is lower as well (all weapons skills are maxed for my level of 5<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> .  At level 44 they should be the same so that is not an issue here for Thunkum.<br>
<br>
Wurmslayer 25/40 = 0.625 (better than my dagger I might add)<br>
<br>
Now, lets look at some numbers shall we?  For the seb dagger and Wurmy to have a time in combat divisible by both delays you would need to fight for 18*40 = 720 seconds (12 minutes)<br>
<br>
Modal damage on these weapons for onhand should be 2 x base damage + damage bonus per hit<br>
<br>
Wurmslayer 25*2+6 = 56      56*18=1008 for 12 minute fight<br>
Seb Dirk     10*2+6 = 26      26*40=1040<br>
<br>
Now, the difference for a 12 minute fight is 32 pts.  Difference in damage from one hit of each is 30 pts.  Most fights won't last 12 minutes and most fights start with delay counter reset so wurmy or dirk should fire immediately and probably make up that one hit at the start of the fight.  If the fight lasts 12 minutes, what are the chances that you will riposte one time as well?  Probably pretty good so we are back to even on damage.  This crude analysis neglects double attack and haste but these are just multipliers of the damage which really should have no effect here for comparison.  Riposte damage favors the Wurmslayer as well, you hit for more when you riposte, and get riposted less because you swing less and the mob makes a riposte check less.<br>
<br>
Therefore, it appears that the Wurmslayer is the same for damage in main hand as Seb Croaking Dirk for this level 44 warrior.  For the offhand ratio and stats should be primary concern IMO.  With Wurmslayer in onhand, Seb Croaking Dirk could go in offhand (ratio is 10/18=0.555) as opposed to Centi LS (ratio is 14/27=0.519).  A bonus to this is that the Dirk is faster and therefore will train up dual wield faster than a centi ls, plus gives 4 AC, a very useful stat for a warrior.<br>
<br>
Thunkum:<br>
<br>
As far as taunting off casters and healers, you may try getting next to the mob you are trying to get off casters.  Make sure you and the caster are not moving.  If the mob is moving taunt rarely seems to work.  Bash the mob, and immediately hit taunt if it looks like it is stunned from the bash.  If it is a mezzed mob, please be chanter friendly and taunt two or three times and then wait for it to refresh before bashing, clicking autoattack, and then hit taunt if it looks stunned.  This has worked well for me on mezzed mobs.  I used to attack after taunting, but bashing and stunning, then attacking, then taunting while mob is still stunned works wonders.<br>
<br>
As you gain levels, you will find it harder and harder to keep aggro from casters and other melee, welcome to being a warrior.  Best thing you can do is try the weapons you have on the same mobs for a little while.  You will soon learn what ones hold aggro better for you.  Like I said, worst thing you can do is experiment with what I said and find that it doesn't work for you.  It shouldn't take that long to figure out a gut feel of what lets you keep aggro better.  If aggro is truely your main concern (damage plays a big part in aggro/taunt though, just look at monks using 2hb) then you may try to find a cheap proc'ing weapon.  Kunzar Ku'juch is an 8/22 1HS that procs engulfing darkness.  Mobs really hate the snare effect on that one and it is relatively fast.  Short Sword of Ykesha procs a 75pt DD which used to get mobs attention for me for many levels.  Both these weapons are dirt cheap now and have a useful proc.<br>
<br>
My 2 cps worth,<br>
<br>
Friedrick - 58th Myrmidom on Tunare server<br>
